@node "Inst" "Installation"

 @{b}IRQuery INSTALLATION@{ub}

Before Installing IRQuery you need to get an account at
http://www.ddns.org. You @{b}CAN NOT@{ub} use IRQuery without an
account! 

The easiest way to install irquery is with the provided Installer
script. You will be asked for a place of this document and the IRQuery
program will be installed in the C: - and the IRQuery.conf script in
the S: directory. N.B.You can not install the IRQuery.conf file in
another directory!!

If you do not use the Config installer script you need to edit the
IRQuery.conf file by hand. Read the configuration file section for
more information.


 @{b}IRQuery CONFIGURATION@{ub}

The Installer script will automatically run the 'Config' Installer
script for configuring the IRQuery client. Beware: the script will
overwrite any existing configuration! You can choose 2 levels of
installation, Average user and Expert user. In the Expert user
level you can set some advanced options. Normally you won't need
them. 

The configuration part will ask you a few questions. If you make
an error, start the configuration part again. The program asks you
for the following information:

* The program asks you first for the output (debug) level of IRQuery.
  Here you can select the amount of output the IRQuery programs
  will produce.

* Your email address you used when you signed up at DDNS.

* Your full hostname for your ddns account. For example: example.ddns.org
  Don't use your hostname 'example'.

* Your registered password.

If you have chosen the expert mode then the following questions are asked:

* Is your IP address dynamic (changes everytime you login, the default) or
  static? (your ip address stays the same, everytime you login)

  - If you selected 'static' You will be asked for your IP address.

* Do you want IROn to run in deamon mode?
  If you run IROn in deamonmode, the program will update your IP address
  automatically every X minutes and set the TIMEOUT to X*2+5 minutes.
  It means that your hostname becomes obsolete after X*2+5 minutes and
  it won't be available after that time. This can be useful if you have
  an unstable connection. IROn will connect with DDNS.org to update the 
  connection every X minutes.

  - if selected 'Yes' you will be asked after how many minutes your hostname
    must be updated at ddns.org.

* Do you have webforwarding enabled?

  If selected 'Yes' you can choose to redirect www.hostname.ddns.org to
  hostname.ddns.org. This means that you need to run your own webserver
  on your computer to have any use for this. For example the Apache
  webserver at: http://www.xs4all.nl/~albertv/apache/

* Do you have Domain Mail Forwarding enabled? (DMF)
  
  If selected 'Yes' you have the possibility to set the MX entry to
  your hostname.ddns.org when you are online. A full mailserver like
  qmail or smail is required.

  Domain Mail forwarding is accomplished by setting the MX entries of 
  hostname.ddns.org to MX hostname mail.ddns.org. MX IP 203.120.99.200. 
  This will redirect all email to hostname.ddns.org to mail.ddns.org, 
  which will do a database lookup and forward the email to the registered 
  account.

* If you didn't select the Deamon mode of IROn, you will be asked if you
  want to enable the TIMEOUT option. Your hostname will become obsolete
  after X minutes you can set here.


For more information about all options, read the commandline and the 
configuration file part of this Amigaguide.

@endnode


@node "Test" "Testing"
 @{b}Testing@{ub}

It is a good idea to test IRQuery first before real use. 
So, make sure you are connected to the internet and run the IRQuery
program from a shell:

       13.DH0:C>IRQuery

the program will answer with:

                IP Registry Query Ver 0.4.7
and a prompt:
                <- 

Set the debuglevel to 2 with the command 'debug':

                <- debug 2

And intialize it with the command 'init':

                <- init
The IRQuery program will connect to the ddns server and gives some
output. For example:

		Initialising Connection...
		(Sent) ID 1
		(Received) OK ID 1
		(Sent) EMAIL rarf@netspire.com.sg
		(Received) OK EMAIL rarf@netspire.com.sg
		(Sent) IP 203.120.99.100
		(Received) OK IP 203.120.99.100
		(Sent) HOST rarf.ddns.org
		(Received) OK HOST rarf.ddns.org
		(Sent) PASS PASSWORD
		(Received) OK PASS PASSWORD

If this succeeds, then you are connected with DDNS and you can give 
commands to the server. First update the server with the command:

		<- update

the server responds with:

                -> OK UPDATE

to test your hostname:

                <- qhost

the server responds with: 

		-> OK QHOST rarf.ddns.org

If this all works you can quit with the command:

		<- quit

and the server will respond with:

		-> OK QUIT

Your computer is now reachable at the address <yourhostname>.ddns.org!

@endnode

@node "Usag" "Usage"
 @{b}Usage@{ub}

Once configured IRQuery, the usage is very simple. Get online, and run
the 'IROn' program from a shell. The IRQuery.conf script in S: is used
automatically.

Before you get offline, you use the 'IROff' program from a shell to
clear your entry.

Of course it is best if you add in your user-startnet script (AmiTCP)
the IROn program and in your stopnet script (AmiTCP) the IROff program
or something similar in Miami.

That's all.

For more advanced options, see the documentation at the
http://www.ddns.org site!

@endnode

@node "Serv" "Services"

 @{b}Available Services at DDNS@{ub}

This is a list of all services available at DDNS. The standard, basic
functions are free, for others there is a low maintance fee.

New subscribers for Enhanced/Advanced chargeable services have a free
trial of 1 month.

@{b}Dynamic DNS@{ub}

Dynamic DNS allows everyone to have a hostname such as cool.ddns.org so
others can connect directly to your machine for applications like FTP,
WWW etc. No more hunting for that elusive IP whenever you dial up your
ISP!

@{b}Cost: Free@{ub}

@{b}Extended Dynamic DNS@{ub}

We can service your domain using Dynamic DNS if you delegate the domain
to us. Subdomains can also be redelegated back to you for regular DNS.
We'll also register and set up your domain for you for a one-time
handling fee of US$20. It is an extension of Dynamic DNS.

@{b}Maintenance Fee of US$20/host/annum.@{ub}

@{b}Domain Delegation@{ub}
We can delegate subdomains under ddns.org to you, so you can manage
your own hosts using a regular DNS server. It is an extension of
Dynamic DNS.

@{b}Maintenance Fee of US$20/host/annum.@{ub}

@{b}Domain Mail Forwarding@{ub}
All emails sent to cool.ddns.org will automatically be sent to
cool@isp.com. You will have an unlimited number of email addresses!

@{b}Cost: Free@{ub}

@{b}Advanced Mail Forwarding@{ub}
Email can be forwarded selectively by addressees. dad@cool.ddns.org's
email will go to dad@isp.com, mom@cool.ddns.org to mom@isp.com, and
kid@cool.ddns.org to kid@isp.com. It is an extension of Domain Mail
Forwarding.

@{b}Maintenance Fee of US$20/host/annum.@{ub}

@{b}Mail Exchange Backup@{ub}
For those receiving its own emails instead of using Mail Forwarding.
Email will be spooled on our mail servers when you're offline instead
of remaining on the originating mail server. When you do come online,
all email will be pushed to you.

@{b}Maintenance Fee of US$20/host/annum.@{ub}

@{b}Web Forwarding@{ub}
Get a customised and easy-to-remember URL for your HomePages!
Connecting to http://www.cool.ddns.org will automatically send them to
your HomePage at http://www.isp.com/~cool.

@{b}Cost: Free@{ub}

@{b}Enhanced Web Forwarding@{ub}
The URL http://www.cool.ddns.org will be shown while accessing your
pages even though actual accesses are to your HomePage at
http://www.isp.com/~cool. You can have an instant webserver anywhere!
It is an extension of Web Forwarding

@{b}Maintenance Fee of US$10/host/annum.@{ub}

Sponsored By:


[Contact Info]
WebMaster: <wwwadmin@ddns.org>
Enquiries: <info@ddns.org>
Sales: <sales@ddns.org>
Technical: <tech@ddns.org>

@endnode

@node "Comm" "Command line options"

There are several commandline options available:


Switch  Parameter	Comments                	Program
--------------------------------------------------------------------
id	1		Overrides ID from the           IROn, IROff
			IRQuery.conf file (default: 1)  IRFind
			Example: iron -id 1             IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
email   a@b.c.d		Overrides EMAIL from the        IROn, IROff
			IRQuery,conf file.              IRQuery
			Example: iron -email a@b.c.d
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ip	1.2.3.4		Overrides IP and GET_IP		IROn
                        Use AUTO to use the IP address  IRQuery
			of your ipaddress.
                        Example: iron -ip 1.2.3.4
				 iron -ip AUTO
--------------------------------------------------------------------
host	a.b.c.d		Overrides HOST			IROn
                        Example: iron -host a.b.c.d	IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
pass	PASSWORD	Overrides PASS			IROn, IROff
			Example: iroff -pass PASSWORD	IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
xpass	PASSWORD        Overrides XPASS			IROn, IROff
			Example: iroff -xpass PASSWORD	IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
list	a@b.c.d		Adds to List of Search 		IRFind
			addresses. Multiple list	IRQuery
			switches allowed.
			Example: irfind -list a@b.c.d
--------------------------------------------------------------------
conf	irquery.conf	Use alternate IRQuery.conf file IROn, IROff
			(Default: s:irquery.conf)	IRFind
			Example: iron -conf irnew.conf	IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
debug	2		Set Debug level (Default 0)     IROn, IROff
			Example: irfind -debug 2	IRFind
							IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
server	proxy.netspire.com.sg				IROn, IROff
			Adds to list of Server Host-    IRFind
			names or IP's. (Default:        IRQuery
			mars.netspire.com.sg) Example:
			iron -server proxy.netspire.com.sg
			iron -server 203.120.99.100
--------------------------------------------------------------------
port	9998		Adds to List of Server Ports	IROn, IROff
			(Default 9999)			IRFind
			Example: iron -port 9998	IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
daemon	20		Set Repeat Loop (Default:       IROn, IRFind
			No Repeat.
			Example: iron -deamon 20
--------------------------------------------------------------------
timeout	5		Set Timeout (Default:		IROn
			No Timeout)
			Example: iron -timeout 5
--------------------------------------------------------------------
dmf	1		Set MX Entries to Hostname &	IROn, IROff
			Dynamic IP; Ignore DMF.         IRQuery
			(Default: 0)
			Example: iron -dmf 1
--------------------------------------------------------------------
dhttp	1		Set www.host.ddns.org to	IROn, IROff
			Ignore DHTTP (Default:0)	IRQuery
			Example: iron -dhttp 1
--------------------------------------------------------------------
tmpfile	/tmp/tmp.ip	Set Temporary File. (Default:   IROn, IROff
			/tmp/irquery.ip)		IRFind
			Example: iron -tmpfile s:tmp.ip IRQuery
--------------------------------------------------------------------
script	INIT, UPDATE	Run Scripted Commands		IROn, IROff
        QUIT            Example: 			IRFind
			irquery -script "INIT,UPDATE,   IRQuery
			QUIT"
--------------------------------------------------------------------

@endnode

@node "Form" "Format of the Configuration file"


@{b}Format the of Configuration File irquery.conf@{ub}

@{b}DEBUG (Needed)@{ub}
Default - 0
0 - No debugging information
1 - Shows Protocol Exchange Messages
2 - Shows All Messages

Example: DEBUG=0

@{b}EMAIL (Needed)@{ub}
Fill in your email address that you wish others to locate you by.
Example: EMAIL=rarf@netspire.com.sg

@{b}PASS/XPASS (Needed)@{ub}
Fill in your desired password.
Example: PASS=PASSWORD or XPASS=PASSWORD
Using XPASS encrypts the password before sending onto the Internet.
If it's your first time accessing the service, the password will be saved.

@{b}IP (Optional)@{ub}
Fill in your static IP if you have one.
Example: IP=203.120.99.100
Otherwise, set it to AUTO.

@{b}HOST (Optional)@{ub}
Fill in your hostname if you have registered for one.
Example: HOST=rarf.ddns.org

@{b}LIST (Optional; Multiple)@{ub}
Each entry consists of the email address that your friend is using in the IP Registry.
Example: LIST=rarf@netspire.com.sg
You may have any number of entries.
They will be searched sequentially by irfind.

@{b}DAEMON (Optional; Not Recommended)@{ub}

Run iron every X minutes.
Example: DAEMON=20

@{b}TIMEOUT (Optional; Not Recommended)@{ub}
Purges entry after X minutes.
Example: TIMEOUT=1440
Removes entry from IP Registry after 1 day.

@{b}DHTTP (Optional; Not Recommended))@{ub}
Over-rides DHTTP when online.
This points www.host.ddns.org to host.ddns.org when iron is run.
iroff will set it back to 203.120.99.200.
Example: DHTTP=1

@{b}DMF (Optional; Not Recommended))@{ub}

Over-rides DMF when online.
This sets the MX entries to host.ddns.org when iron is run.
iroff will set it back to mail.ddns.org (203.120.99.200).
Example: DMF=1

@{b}GET_IP (Optional; Obselete)@{ub}

This will be executed to find out your IP.
The output should consist of the IP in string representation.
Example: GET_IP=/sbin/ifconfig ppp0 | grep "inet addr:" | gawk '{print $2}' | cut -c 6-
If it's absent and IP is not set, the program will prompt you for your IP for updating the IP Registry.

@endnode

